<paragraph blockId="38.[151,1436,294,2017]" lastBlockId="39.[151,1436,158,222]" lastPageId="39" lastPageNumber="236" pageId="38" pageNumber="235">
Finally, I consider it useful to add that the examination of the many specimens preserved in the collections of MSNG, of the pair from 
<collectingCountry box="[481,582,1651,1677]" name="Bulgaria" pageId="38" pageNumber="235">Bulgaria</collectingCountry>
kindly sent to me for study by Michel Secq, and of the specimens from Frasassi (CPV), showed that very few specimens possess, on the pigidium, the famous “ 
<emphasis box="[1211,1377,1689,1714]" italics="true" pageId="38" pageNumber="235">ligne médiane</emphasis>
[…] 
<emphasis box="[151,203,1727,1752]" italics="true" pageId="38" pageNumber="235">lisse</emphasis>
” described by 
<bibRefCitation author="Auzat, V." box="[383,540,1727,1753]" pageId="38" pageNumber="235" pagination="145 - 147" refId="ref72328" refString="Auzat, V. (1923) Description d'un nouveau Gnathoncus de Sardaigne (Coleopt. Hist.). Bollettino della Societa Entomologica Italiana, 55 (10), 145 - 147." type="journal article" year="1923">Auzat (1923)</bibRefCitation>
and which according to this author “ 
<emphasis box="[982,1276,1727,1752]" italics="true" pageId="38" pageNumber="235">distingue à première vue</emphasis>
<taxonomicName authorityName="Auzat" authorityYear="1923" box="[1285,1436,1727,1753]" class="Insecta" family="Histeridae" genus="Gnathoncus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="38" pageNumber="235" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="cerberus">Gn. cerberus</taxonomicName>
<emphasis box="[151,489,1765,1790]" italics="true" pageId="38" pageNumber="235">des autres espèces du genre</emphasis>
<taxonomicName box="[499,646,1765,1791]" class="Insecta" family="Histeridae" genus="Gnathoncus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="38" pageNumber="235" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Gnathoncus</taxonomicName>
”. This feature, highlighted by all subsequent authors (e.g. 
<bibRefCitation author="Vienna, P." pageId="38" pageNumber="235" refId="ref76703" refString="Vienna, P. (1980) Fauna d'Italia XVI. Coleoptera Histeridae. Calderini, Bologna, 373 pp." type="book" year="1980">Vienna 1980</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Thomas, H. &amp; Secq, M." box="[227,494,1802,1828]" pageId="38" pageNumber="235" pagination="207 - 208" refId="ref76622" refString="Thomas, H. &amp; Secq, M. (2000) Gnathoncus cerberus Auzat, 1923: une espece nouvelle pour la faune Bulgare (Coleoptere Histeridae). Bulletin de la Societe Linneenne de Bordeaux, 28 (4), 207 - 208." type="journal article" year="2000">Thomas &amp; Secq 2000</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Lackner, T. &amp; Pavicevic, D." box="[509,831,1802,1828]" pageId="38" pageNumber="235" pagination="423 - 426" refId="ref74144" refString="Lackner, T. &amp; Pavicevic, D. (2008) Faunistic note on newly recorded and rare species of Histeridae from Serbia (Coleoptera). In: Pavicevic, D. &amp; Perreau, M. (Eds), Advances in the studies of the fauna of the Balkan Peninsula. Papers dedicated to the memory of Guido Nonveiller. Institute for Nature Conservation of Serbia, Belgrade, Monograph 22, pp. 423 - 426." type="journal article" year="2008">Lackner &amp; Pavićević 2008</bibRefCitation>
) and always used in the identification keys of the Palearctic species of the genus 
<taxonomicName authority="Jacquelin du Val" authorityName="Jacquelin du Val" box="[528,883,1840,1866]" class="Insecta" family="Histeridae" genus="Gnathoncus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="38" pageNumber="235" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[528,670,1841,1866]" italics="true" pageId="38" pageNumber="235">Gnathoncus</emphasis>
Jacquelin du Val
</taxonomicName>
, is deceitful and often misleading considering that a smooth, median longitudinal band is sometimes more or less obvious in specimens of 
<taxonomicName authority="(Kugelann)" baseAuthorityName="Kugelann" baseAuthorityYear="1792" class="Insecta" family="Histeridae" genus="Gnathoncus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="38" pageNumber="235" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="rotundatus">
<emphasis box="[1270,1291,1878,1903]" italics="true" pageId="38" pageNumber="235">G</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis box="[1309,1436,1878,1903]" italics="true" pageId="38" pageNumber="235">rotundatus</emphasis>
(Kugelann)
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authority="(Marseul)" baseAuthorityName="Marseul" baseAuthorityYear="1862" box="[353,662,1916,1942]" class="Insecta" family="Histeridae" genus="Gnathoncus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="38" pageNumber="235" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="nannetensis">
<emphasis box="[353,374,1916,1941]" italics="true" pageId="38" pageNumber="235">G</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis box="[395,533,1916,1941]" italics="true" pageId="38" pageNumber="235">nannetensis</emphasis>
(Marseul)
</taxonomicName>
(Penati pers. obs.; Secq 
<emphasis box="[980,1092,1916,1941]" italics="true" pageId="38" pageNumber="235">in litteris</emphasis>
). On the contrary, the best character for distinguishing 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Auzat" authorityYear="1923" box="[481,618,1954,1980]" class="Insecta" family="Histeridae" genus="Gnathoncus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="38" pageNumber="235" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="cerberus">
<emphasis box="[481,502,1954,1979]" italics="true" pageId="38" pageNumber="235">G</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis box="[516,618,1954,1979]" italics="true" pageId="38" pageNumber="235">cerberus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
from all other species with smooth intervals between the punctuation at the tip of the elytra is, in my opinion, the particular sculpture of the pygidium, characterized by transversely elongate punctures, set far apart and lying on an almost completely smooth surface; these punctures are instead more marked and more tightly set in the other species.
</paragraph>
